{
  "answer": "**In the Falsafa corpus, Muhammad Iqbal (Allama Iqbal) uses the term \"tafakkur\" once, in his Urdu poem \"Himalaya\" from *Bang-e-Dara* (Part 1, chapter 25).**[^1]\n\nThere, it evokes an atmosphere or \"samaan\" (mood/ambiance) of deep contemplation or reflection that descends upon the trees amid the profound evening silence of the Himalayan mountains—a state so enchanting that \"speech itself would die to be\" part of it.[^2] The surrounding lines describe nature's evening hush (\"Khamoshi-e-shaam\") drawing the heart, with twilight's trembling hues enhancing the scene, blending sensory beauty and introspective stillness.[^3]\n\nThis poetic usage portrays *tafakkur* as a immersive, almost tangible spiritual or meditative presence in nature, aligning with Iqbal's themes of awakening the inner self (*khudi*) through beauty and divine signs in the world. However, the corpus contains only Iqbal's Urdu poetry (*Bang-e-Dara* Parts 1–3) with translations/transliterations—no prose works like *The Reconstruction of Religious Thought in Islam* where he might elaborate philosophically on reflection or contemplation. No other explicit discussions of *tafakkur* appear in his works here, nor do English equivalents like \"contemplation\" or \"reflection\" link directly to him.\n\n[^1]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-e-Dara Part 1*, chapter 25 \"Himalaya\" (transliteration), [paragraph](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-1-55b25c/25-himalaya/transliteration/#p-81b343). The sole hit for \"tafakkur\" across Iqbal's poetry.\n\n[^2]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-e-Dara Part 1*, chapter 25 \"Himalaya\" (translation), [paragraph](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-1-55b25c/25-himalaya/translation/#p-a44a02). Translates \"Darakhton par tafakkur ka samaan chhaaya hua\" as \"That thoughtful mood that settles over every tree.\"\n\n[^3]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-e-Dara Part 1*, chapter 25 \"Himalaya\" (translation), [paragraphs](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-1-55b25c/25-himalaya/translation/#p-1dc1b0-p-a44a02-p-638558). Full context: waterfall sounds ensnaring the heart, evening silence, and twilight on the peaks.",
